      <abstract displayLabel="Abstract">Version 5.0 of the database was released in December 2023. Most
                screens were redesigned. An option was added to provide samplers of polar
                elastic-scattering angles that can be used in Monte Carlo simulations of electron
                transport in solids (as was possible in Version 3.2 and earlier versions). However,
                a more accurate numerical method has been implemented in Version 5.0, as described
                in Appendix A. The new sampler is designed to generate scattering angles for
                electron energies between 50 eV and 20 keV. The differential elastic-scattering
                cross sections (DCSs) were calculated using the relativistic Dirac partial-wave
                method, as described by Walker [3]. The scattering potential was obtained from the
                self-consistent Dirac-Hartree-Fock electron density for free atoms [4] with the
                local exchange potential of Furness and McCarthy [5]. The numerical calculations
                were performed with the algorithm described by Salvat and Mayol [6]. Transport cross
                sections were calculated from the DCSs as described by Jablonski et al.
                [1].</abstract>
